'''Emeel Badie Salem, Jr.''' (born February 11, 1985 in [[Birmingham, Alabama]]) is a [[professional baseball]] player in the [[Tampa Bay Rays]] organization. He bats and throws [[left-handed]], and primarily plays [[center field]]. Salem attended the [[University of Alabama]] from 2004 to 2007 and received many awards while playing for the [[Alabama Crimson Tide baseball]] team. He was also awarded for his achievements as a [[student-athlete]], including becoming the first [[college baseball]] player to win the [[Lowe's Senior CLASS Award]] in 2007 after achieving a 3.85 [[grade point average]] from his [[freshman]] to [[senior (education)|senior]] years in college. He was drafted by the Rays in the [[2007 Major League Baseball Draft]]. Although Salem has never played in [[Major League Baseball]], he has played for the Class-A Short-Season [[Hudson Valley Renegades]] (2007), the Class-A [[Columbus Catfish]] (2008), the Class-A Advanced [[Charlotte Stone Crabs]] (2009), and the Double-A [[Montgomery Biscuits]] (2010) in the [[minor league baseball|minors]]. Over his career, he has primarily played center field, however, Salem has played [[left field]], [[right field]] and [[designated hitter]].

==Amateur career==
Salem attended [[Mountain Brook High School]] in [[Mountain Brook, Alabama]] and later the [[University of Alabama]]. During his [[freshman]] season at Alabama, Salem [[batting average|batted]] .304 with 16 [[run (baseball)|runs]], 21 [[hit (baseball)|hits]], two [[double (baseball)|doubles]], one [[home run]], 11 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs) and five [[stolen bases]] in 41 games. In 2005, Salem's [[sophomore]] season, he batted .277 with 31 runs, 56 hits, four doubles, three [[triple (baseball)|triples]], 14 RBIs, 13 stolen bases and seven [[caught stealing]] in 59 games. On May 1, 2006, during his [[junior (education)|junior]] season, Salem won the [[Louisville Slugger]] National Player of the Week awarded by ''[[Collegiate Baseball Newspaper]]'', and was named [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) Player of the Week.<ref name="scout"/> At the end of the season, Salem was awarded the Southeastern Conference Scholar-Athlete of the Year award as voted upon by the 12 SEC [[coach (baseball)|head coaches]].<ref name="scout all star">{{cite web |url=http://alabama.scout.com/2/533673.html |title=Tide All-Stars |author= |date=May 23, 2006 |work=University of Alabama Media Relations |publisher=Scout.com |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> As of May 23, 2006. he was [[double major|double majoring]] in [[marketing]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and sustained a 3.9 [[grade point average]].<ref name="scout all star"/> From 2004 to 2006, Salem made the SEC Academic [[Honor Roll]] and in 2006 was selected to the coach's First-Team All-SEC team.<ref name="scout all star"/> On the 2006 season, he Salem batted .356 with 67 runs, 101 hits, 14 doubles, seven triples, two home runs, 32 RBIs, and 36 stolen bases. In the [[2006 Major League Baseball Draft]], Salem was drafted by the [[Baltimore Orioles]] in the tenth round, but did not sign.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/?year_ID=2006&draft_round=10&draft_type=junreg&query_type=year_round |title=10th Round of the 2006 MLB June Amateur Draft |author= |date= |work=Baseball-Reference |publisher=Sports Reference, LLC |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> On June 13, 2006, Salem and teammate [[Wade LeBlanc]] were named to the [[American Baseball Coaches Association]] (ABCA) First-Team All-South Region team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alabama.scout.com/2/539203.html |title=LeBlanc, Salem Named to ABCA All-South Region |author= |date=June 13, 2006 |work=University of Alabama Media Relations |publisher=Scout.com |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> 

Before his [[senior (education)|senior]] season in 2007, Salem was named to the [[Brooks Wallace Award]] and Dick Howser Trophy watch list.<ref name="preseason"/> He was also named a pre-season All-American by the College Baseball Foundation, [[Rivals.com]] and the [[National Collegiate Baseball Writers Association]].<ref name="preseason">{{cite web |url=http://www.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/uwire/012607aac.html |title=Alabama's Salem focused on the present |author=Will Barry |date=January 26, 2007 |work=The Crimson White |publisher=CBS College Sports |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> On his academic success, Salem commented, "I really do take pride in my grades...When a lot of guys go out and everything, I'm in the library studying. So, I definitely make the sacrifices."<ref name="preseason"/> On his 22{{sup|nd}} birth day, Salem hit two home runs in his first two [[at-bats]] in a game against [[Georgia State University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alabama.scout.com/2/618158.html |title=Salem Has Two-Homer Birthday Bash |author=Barry Allen |date=February 11, 2007 |work=University of Alabama Media Relations |publisher=Scout.com |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> In 2007, Salem was nominated by the University of Alabama for the H. Boyd McWhorter Scholar-Athlete Post-Graduate [[Scholarship]] and received the [[Algernon Sydney Sullivan Award]] after sustaining a 3.85 grade point average after his senior year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alabama.scout.com/2/628348.html |title=And The UofA Nominees Are |author= |date=March 20, 2007 |work=University of Alabama Media Relations |publisher=Scout.com |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> He later won the H. Boyd McWhorter Scholar-Athlete Post-Graduate Scholarship, which was awarded to him at the annual SEC spring meeting in [[Destin, Florida]], on May 31, 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alabama.scout.com/2/633270.html |title=Tide Baseball<U+2019>s Salem Honored |author= |date=April 6, 2007 |work=Southeastern Conference Media Relations |publisher=Scout.com |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> On April 17, 2007, it was announced that Salem, along with 30 other [[college baseball]] players, were finalists for the [[Lowe's Senior CLASS Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alabama.scout.com/2/636315.html |title=Emeel Salem Senior Finalist |author= |date=April 17, 2007 |work=University of Alabama Media Relations |publisher=Scout.com |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> Salem was named to the [[ESPN the Magazine]]'s First-Team Academic All-American Team, making it his second consecutive season to receive that honor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wtvy.com/sports/headlines/7744757.html |title=Tide's Salem gets ESPN the Magazine award |author= |date=May 30, 2007 |work=Associated Press |publisher=Gray Interactive Media |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> Salem won the inaugural Lowe's Senior CLASS Award after beating out 29 other finalists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alabama.scout.com/2/654350.html |title=Salem Is First Winner Of Award |author= |date=June 25, 2007 |work=University of Alabama Media Relations |publisher=Scout.com |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> Salem was named to the National Collegiate Baseball Writers Association All-American Team after the 2007 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nWk1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=66cEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1468,73643&dq=emeel+salem&hl=en |title=Emeel Salem gets All-America honors |author= |date=June 16, 2007 |work=The Tuscaloosa News |publisher=The Tuscaloosa News |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> On the 2007 season, his final at Alabama, Salem batted .351 with 61 runs, 81 hits, seven doubles, three triples, seven home runs, 32 RBIs, and 23 stolen bases in 57 games.

==Professional career==
The [[Tampa Bay Devil Rays]] (now known as the Tampa Bay Rays) drafted Salem in the sixth round of the [[2007 Major League Baseball Draft]].<ref name="tampa bay">{{cite web |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2007/06/09/Rays/Scouts_see_potential_.shtml |title=Scouts see potential at position spots |author=Marc Topkin |date=June 9, 2007 |work=St. Petersburg Times |publisher=St. Petersburg Times |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> Salem began his professional career with the Class-A Short-Season [[Hudson Valley Renegades]]. With the Renegades, he [[batting average|batted]] .311 with 41 [[run (baseball)|runs]], 70 [[hit (baseball)|hits]], 11 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], seven [[triple (baseball)|triples]], one [[home run]], 23 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs) and 28 [[stolen bases]] in 58 games. Salem was tied for second in the [[New York <U+2013> Penn League]] in triples and was third in stolen bases.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/leader.cgi?type=bat&id=13046&sort_by=SB |title=2007 New York-Pennsylvania League Batting Leaders |author= |date= |work=Baseball-Reference |publisher=Sports Reference, LLC |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> He was selected to the New York <U+2013> Penn League Post-Season All-Star team after the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bizofbaseball.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1753&Itemid=42 |title=Topps Names Rays MLB Organization of the Year |author=Maury Brown |date=December 5, 2007 |work=The Biz of Baseball |publisher=Business of Sports Network |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> In 2008, Salem spent the entire season with the Class-A [[Columbus Catfish]]. During the month of April, the Tampa Bay Rays named Salem the Player of the Month in their [[minor league baseball|minor league]] organization.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3637848 |title=Tampa Bay Recognizes Salem as Minor League Player of the Month |author= |date=May 9, 2008 |work=OurSports Central |publisher=OurSports Central |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> On May 16, 2008, Salem was placed on the [[disabled list]] after he broke his [[elbow]] from [[slide (baseball)|sliding]] head-first into [[second base]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3641789 |title=Salem, Ragan Placed on Disabled List |author= |date=May 16, 2008 |work=OurSports Central |publisher=OurSports Central |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> His injury was season ending and he spent the rest of the season rehabbing at Naimoli Complex in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alabama.scout.com/a.z?s=14&p=2&c=762517 |title=Salem Looks To Come Back Strong In 2009 |author=Kathy Gierer |date=June 16, 2008 |work=RaysDigest.com |publisher=Scout.com |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> In 38 games, Salem batted .301 with 24 runs, 26 hits, four doubles, three triples, seven RBIs, and 25 stolen bases. Salem began the season with the Class-A Advanced [[Charlotte Stone Crabs]]. On the season, Salem batted .255 with 54 runs, 91 hits, 12 doubles, seven triples, 22 RBIs, and 24 stolen bases in 99 games. He led the team in triples.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=41627 |title=2009 Charlotte Stone Crabs |author= |date= |work=Baseball-Reference |publisher=Sports Reference, LLC |accessdate=July 30, 2010}}</ref> Salem was assigned to the Double-A [[Montgomery Biscuits]] where he currently plays.

==Other activities==
Salem led the Pinnacle Baseball Camp, a camp for baseball players in grades [[kindergarten]] to [[eighth grade]].<ref name="Camp">{{cite web |url=http://www.sandmountainreporter.com/story.lasso?ewcd=4dc750b91d221167 |title=Registration continues for Pinnacle Camp |author= |date=February 19, 2009 |work=Sand Mountain Reporter |publisher=Sand Mountain Reporter |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> Along with Salem, other professional players instructed the camp including [[second baseman]] [[Matt Downs]] and [[shortstop]] Greg Paiml.<ref name="Camp"/>

==Personal==
Salem's father, Emeel Salem, Sr., was drafted by the [[Chicago Cubs]] out of high school but chose to attended the [[University of South Alabama]] where he played baseball under [[coach (baseball)|coach]] [[Eddie Stanky]].<ref name="preseason"/> Salem is a [[concert pianist]] and speaks several different [[language]]s.<ref name="tampa bay"/> Salem is also related to [[football]] players [[Ed Salem]], George Salem, Sr., George Salem, Jr. and Jimbo Salem.<ref name="scout">{{cite web |url=http://alabama.scout.com/2/526787.html |title=Salem Honored |author=Kirk McNair |date=May 1, 2006 |work='BamaMag.com |publisher=Scout.com |accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref><ref name="preseason"/>

